H E I R L O O M // when M approached me with this project, I admit, I hesitated. She asked me to set a family stone, passed down for generations. This Aquamarine was just gorgeous... And also handcut.

That meant the underside of the oval Aquamarine was not symmetrical or even, which is typical for stones cut that many years ago. Setting the stone was incredibly challenging, as the stone had to be set very specifically and the seat I cut had to fit the variations perfectly.

The end result - you would never know! And that's the point. We used 14k white gold to showcase the blue in the stone. I love the challenge this heirloom stone brought and am proud to have created a dainty piece M can wear and honor her family history with.

I don't take on every rework or setting request I get, I lean into my current skillset and comfort levels, balancing ideas, budgets, and timelines, but I'm always interested to learn about project ideas, daydream designs, and see if what my clients ask for is within my wheelhouse! Dream big, right?
.
.
.

B A N D S // when S & E reached out about custom wedding bands, I was immediately excited. S had an heirloom family ring we had to pair it with and we needed very specific measurements. The family ring was floral and art deco and had several little tufts and accents that jutted out, making the pairing ever so tricky.

We were able to balance the needs of each of them with a delicate band sprinkled with 6 little 1mm diamonds and a central 1.5mm focal diamond (total 0.05 ctw diamonds). To me, just the right amount of sparkle, but also 7 chances to ruin and totally mangle the ring at the finish line 😂) this ring challenged my focus in such a new way! For E we created a smooth contour band that was refined and elegant.

What really made this project special is that S&E knew from the jump they wanted to work with LanaBetty and travelled from Alberta to do their fittings and let me measure the engagement ring. They were so supportive and kind and genuine and I hope every goldsmith finds clients as wonderful as them!

While I love making sets of rings, it really just makes my heart sing to be included in any part of the whole "I love you forever" process 😊🥰😛
.
.

S P E C I A L // is the word I would use to describe this project. When my client asked me to set a new stone in the ring she had as a child, so she could gift it to her only granddaughter, my heart melted and I agreed. This ring had clear hallmarks on it, so I was able to identify it was 10k gold, though it definitely had some tarnish from over the years! We agreed on a blue gemstone, Iolite, to remind her of her September birthstone (I mean, this granddaughter is under age 10, so we weren't really in a position to go for sapphires). I replaced the claws and set the new stone! It turned out so stunning. I know that this little recipient is going to treasure this ring from grandma, so very much.
- - -
I don't often take on projects like this, stone sizes now versus 40 years ago have changed and sometimes we can't authenticate the quality of the metal and I just don't want to mess with the unknown. I am glad it all worked out so well!
- - -
If you're looking for a one of a kind piece or want to rework an heirloom piece, reach out! Let's talk ☺

L A Y E R S // here are 4 quick styling tips for layered necklaces 👇
These will help you execute your new style effortlessly.

➡ Consider mixing metals - for a contemporary take on layered necklaces, try wearing different metals simultaneously. This means you can wear your favourite silver and gold jewelry  together!

➡ Choose one statement piece - choosing one statement necklace, for example a long Mantra piece can create a centerpiece for your look. Allow this necklace to do the talking while the others support it.

➡ Have a variety in necklace weights - choosing a mixture of chunky necklaces and skinny chains, as well as different textured necklaces, can add a touch of intrigue to a layered necklace look. Use a mixture of paperclip chains, curb chains, and bead chains.

➡ Switch up your necklaces with pendants - if you like to change your look frequently, having the same base chains but adding different pendants dependent on occasion is a great way to add versatility.

Although there are many aspects you may want to think about when choosing how to layer necklaces, the job can be kept simple and always looks good.

B A C K  S T O R Y // growing up I didn't always want to be a goldsmith. I actually wanted to study medicine. When I made my way to university, I found developmental biology and cell signalling and fell in love with the way our bodies worked. Little did I know, but it was a super niche area of study and post graduate jobs were few and far between. But I had learned how to learn and those skills gave me the foundation to build this business and my love of jewelry design.

Fast forward a few years and I was working in a laboratory, testing and sampling wine 🍷 and I realized if I didn't make a change, I would work in that lab the rest of my life. To some that stability may have been reassuring, but to me it felt like a coup de grâce and my eventuality was written in stone.

So I began to explore jewelry design. And create. And do a couple pop ups. Then I built a website. And explored product photography, graphic design, stone setting. Layer by layer, step by step, growing my skills and accomplishments and weaving this incredible tapestry of my business into the beauty you see today. How I got here hasn't been easy, but I have surely enjoyed every step. And I am so excited for what's to come.

See me in booth A05 at the One of a Kind Show (@ooak_toronto) to see my full collection.
